		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Assignments to learn network programming
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1737994">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							For network programming, it depends on what level of network you'll be programming.  Review the list of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OSI_model" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">OSI layers</a> and focus on the part that seems most relevant.  Each layer has bunch of protocols and it probably won't be too hard to come up with some study goals once you pick out the protocols you want to learn.  The OSI stuff itself on the wiki page is interesting from an academic context but if you're looking for exercises and hard knowledge it's probably not worth your time.  Studying the actual protocol details is a much better use of time.<br />
<br />
On second though, actually I'd recommend focusing on <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TCP/IP_reference_model" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">the TCP/IP stack</a>.  The OSI model distinction between session, transport, and presentation aren't as practical now.<br />
<br />
I think the best way to figure out middle layers (TCP/UDP/IP) is to set up your own network and do some packet capture.  The goal wouldn't be to write applications, just understand how networks work.  If you decide that writing systems-level apps with remote procedure calls and such is really what you want to be doing, you can spend more time on it.<br />
<br />
But if you want to be writing distributed applications for some purpose other than improving the performance of a network itself, odds are that you will be focused on the application-layer protocols that already exist, like HTTP, SMTP, NFS, etc..  Most decent programming languages have libraries or even whole frameworks for writing network applications.  Even if you wanted to write a new protocol, such as for a network videogame or something, you'd probably want to study some of the existing protocols to see how they work.<br />
<br />
The telnet protocol is one of the simplest protocols and can be a good tool for learning about the other protocols.  For instance, so long as there are no issues with encryption, you can make a telnet connection to an SMTP server or HTTP server and simply type in the commands from the relevant protocol to see how they work.  Here's me typing &quot;telnet <a href="http://www.graffe.com" target="_blank">www.graffe.com</a> 80&quot; to make a TCP connection to graffe's on port 80.  Then I type &quot;GET /&quot; to get the root page, which of course doesn't work too well, probably because I'm not using a real browser, but you get the idea.<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>HTTPGET</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Code:</div>
	<pre class="bbcode_code"style="height:228px;">$ telnet www.graffe.com 80
Trying 184.106.55.19...
Connected to www.graffe.com.
Escape character is '^]'.
GET /
&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC &quot;-//WC3//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN&quot;&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;head&gt;
        &lt;title&gt;Coming Soon page&lt;/title&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
    &lt;center&gt;
        &lt;p&gt;Please come back later.&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;/center&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
Connection closed by foreign host.</pre>
</div> 
</div>
</div>
</div>Most modern languages have libraries that wrap these protocol commands.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representational_state_transfer" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">REST</a> is a bunch of conventions for using HTTP to write distributed applications.  Often web apps are written with a &quot;RESTful&quot; API.  I don't have a lot of experience with this personally.  <br />
<br />
I also can't give much advice on parallel computing, but I can recommend you take a look at <a href="http://web.mit.edu/star/cluster/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">StarCluster</a> to get an idea for how an HPC cluster typically works.  StarCluster is a tool that can deploy <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oracle_Grid_Engine" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">Sun Grid Engine</a> on amazon EC2.<br />
<br />
For large-scale applications you'll probably also want to look up MapReduce programming style as well as some knowledge of the various RDBMS and noSQL database systems available.<br />
<br />
Anyway this is sort of a haphazard list of comments, but hopefully you'll find something useful to at least find some direction.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
		<div class="postfoot">
