		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Assignments to learn network programming
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1738042">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Mihoko Ishii</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1738041#post1738041" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Also, I suppose technically speaking I have written scripts/programs which would qualify as having utilized network programming as they interacted with an API that downloaded data which I then worked with, but I'm interested in learning how to write the code that would make up the API that I was interacting with.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I'm familiar with python, but you could probably find equivalents in other languages, but I would try:<br />
<br />
<a href="http://docs.python.org/library/socket.html" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">socket</a> programming is probably where you'd start if you were going to build a network application from scratch.  Sockets are an OS concept, I'm not familiar with mobile devices but I doubt that the mobile OS's have moved far from the socket model.  Windows and Linux both provide socket APIs, you can write the network code in C/C++ or use a wrapper library like the python one I linked.<br />
<br />
If you want to see an example of a small but production-capable webserver built on the socket library (among others) you might try reading the code for <a href="http://www.cherrypy.org/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">cherrypy</a>.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
